# Test Strategy (Planning Phase)

Quality decisions during planning prevent wasted effort writing tests flagged in review.

> **Companion skills/rules**: `bdd-story-analysis` skill (`skills/bdd-story-analysis/SKILL.md`) (scenarios, pyramid, test levels), framework-specific rules (syntax/tooling), `test-usefulness` skill (`skills/test-usefulness/SKILL.md`) (anti-patterns to avoid during planning).

## Choose the Right Test Level

Test at the lowest level that catches the bug.

| If the logic is... | Plan a... | Not a... |
|---|---|---|
| Pure function (validation, formatting, calculation) | Unit test calling it directly | Component/controller/integration test |
| Module with internal dependencies | Integration test with real or stubbed collaborators | E2E test |
| UI component with user interaction | Integration test with DOM testing library | E2E test |
| Full user journey or multi-service flow | E2E test (critical paths only) | Integration test with excessive mocking |

## Verify Happy Path First

Before planning error/edge tests, confirm happy path tests exist. If a story adds error handling:

- At least one test exercises the successful flow
- Happy path wasn't removed by current changes

If missing → plan happy path as the first test task. Error tests without a baseline prove graceful failure but not that it works.

## Plan Complete Error Coverage

Enumerate **every** error the implementation handles — don't list "test error handling" with a sample of 3/7 codes. Each gets its own test case or parameterized row:

- Every error code the caller/UI responds to
- Every validation rule with a distinct message
- Every conditional redirect, fallback, or exception filter

## Assert on Behavior, Not Internals

| Assert on... | Not on... |
|---|---|
| Response status codes and bodies | Internal method call counts |
| Rendered text, state, navigation | Internal function invocations |
| User/caller-visible error messages | Internal exception types |
| Return values and output state | Private field values |
| Database state (integration) | Repository method call counts |

Planning question: "If internals were refactored without changing caller/user behavior, would this test still pass?"

## Plan Edge Cases

Scan per behavior — only include relevant ones. Reference the `edge-case-heuristics` skill (`skills/edge-case-heuristics/SKILL.md`) for detailed checklists.

| Category | Plan for |
|---|---|
| Boundaries | n-1, n, n+1 for every limit |
| Empty/zero/null | Zero items, empty strings, missing params |
| State | Mid-operation failures, stale data, concurrent access |
| Interruptions | Network loss, timeout, session expiry |
| Conditional branches | Both sides of `\|\|`/`&&`/`??`, each fallback step, null at each optional chain level |
| Context variation | Non-default route, locale, role, tenant, environment, feature flags |

## Planning Checklist

- [ ] Compound ACs decomposed into individual testable requirements (split lists, "mentioned below" references, embedded scenarios in Notes/Technical Details)
- [ ] Happy path tests exist or are planned for every unit under change
- [ ] Each decomposed AC has a test at a specific pyramid level
- [ ] UI components have planned accessibility tests (keyboard navigation, screen reader compatibility, WCAG compliance)
- [ ] Error paths enumerated individually, not grouped
- [ ] Compound conditions and fallback chains have each branch tested
- [ ] Assertions target observable behavior, not internals
- [ ] Relevant edge case categories addressed
- [ ] No test planned at a higher level than necessary
- [ ] Each test verifies one behavior (name describes what it tests)
